Introduction¶

In this project we explore the the TMDb movie data to identify and investigate patterns and relationships between/among the features in the data that can help draw meaningful conclusions on what influences the popularity and general success of movies.

Dataset Description¶

The dataset has 10866 entries and 21 columns. Below are column names and what they represent.

  1. id -------------- unique index of each movie

  2. imdb_id ----------- ----imdb index

  3. popularity ----------- ---measure of how polular a movie is

  4. budget ------------- amount of money spent on the movie

  5. revenue------------- amount of money made from the movie

  6. original_title -------- movie title

  7. cast ----------- actors in the movie

  8. homepage --------------- webpage of the movie

  9. director ---------------movie director

  10. tagline ------------- slogan of the movie

  11. keywords----------- keywords in the movie

  12. overview -------------- blurb of the movie

  13. runtime ------------- length of the movie in mimutes

  14. genres ------- the style categories that the movie falls into

  15. production_companies-------- company that produced the movie

  16. release_date --------------- when the movie was released

  17. vote_count ----------- number of people who liked the movie

  18. vote_average ------------ average of vote count

  19. release_year ---------- the year the movie was realeased

  20. budget_adj ------ movie budget in terms of 2010 dollars

  21. revenue_adj -------- movie revenuw in terms of 2010 dollars

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  1. Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  1. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

Results from assessing the movie dataset¶

The movie dataset has $10866$ entries and $21$ columns. $5$ of the columns have integer type values, $4$ have float type values and the rest have string or object type values.

The unique values in each column vary from $56$ to $10865$.

Additionally, from the information about the data, we see that columns named; homepage, tagline, keywords, overview, genres, director, cast and production_companies have missing values.

Now we do not need all the columns for our analysis so drop the columns that we do not need. The columns: id, imdb_id, homepage, overview, tagline and keywords are dropped.

We also drop the columns cast, director and production_comanies because we see that they have unique values which are almost have of the dataset. While they could be factors that influence the popularity of movies, it may not be very interesting to investigate. So the number of columns reduce to $12$.

From the summary statistics, we see among other things that the maximum popularity value is $32.985763$.

We proceed to clean the reduced dataset.

Data Cleaning¶

The next step is to clean the data. We look out for the following:

missing values

incorrect datatypes

Results from cleaning the dataset¶

missing values: from assessment, the column genres has $23$ missing values. Given that the data type is string and the missing values are not too many, we drop these missing values.

incorrect datatypes: all the columns of the dataset are in have the appropriate data type format so there is no need to make changes.

duplicates: there is one duplicate in the dataset and we remove it.

Now that we have a clean dataset we proceed to explore the relationships between the columns using visuals.

#function for plotting 

def plotting(y,x):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    plot = plt.scatter(x= x, y= y, data= nmovies, color = 'r')
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y)
    plt.title(x + ' and ' + y)
    plt.show()
    return plot
    plt.show()

Research Question 1 ( what is the relationship between popularity and budget ?)¶

In [17]:
nmovies=nmovie_data.sort_values(by=['popularity'], ascending =False).head(50)
plotting('popularity', 'budget')
plt.show()

Given the number of entries in the dataset we sort the data by the column popularity and plot the first $50$ most popular entries against their budgets.

It is observed from the scatterplot that there is little to no association with the popularity and budget. Except for $3$ outliers that have popularity above $20$ and a budget below $200$ million, all top $50$ popular movies in the dataset, have popularity less than or equal to $15$.

Research Question 2 ( what is the relationship between popularity and runtime?)¶

In [18]:
plotting( 'popularity', 'runtime')
plt.show()

Plotting the top $50$ popular movies against their runtime, reveals that ,ost movies have runtime between $75$ minutes and $175$ minutes. Similar to the budget, it can be observed that there is very little association between popularity and the runtime of a movie.

Research Question 3 (What has been the general popularity of movies from year to year?)¶

In [19]:
poplarity_pattern = nmovie_data.groupby('release_year').sum().reset_index().tail(25)
poplarity_pattern.plot.bar(x='release_year',y='popularity', figsize = (12,8), color='r', xlabel= 'years', ylabel = 'sum popularity', 
                           title ="General popularity of movies over the years")
plt.show()

We would also like to investigate the general popularity of movies over the years, irrespective of genres. We sum the popularity of movies by release year. For visibility, the plot starts from the year $1991$ and we see that the general trend in the popularity of movies is an upward trend. We however see that in some years such as, $2000$, $2010$ and $2012$ there is a dip in the popularity of movies which could be caused by external factors outside the movie industry or space.

Research Question 3 (Which genre has the highest popularity?)¶

In [20]:
temp2 = nmovie_data.groupby('genres').sum().reset_index()
category = {}
for (elm1,elm2) in temp2[['genres','popularity']].values:
    splt = elm1.split('|')
    for elm3 in splt:
        if (elm3 not in category ):
            category[elm3] = elm2
        else:
            category[elm3] += elm2
In [22]:
temp3 = nmovie_data.groupby(['genres','release_year']).sum().reset_index()
category= {}
for (elm1,elm2) in temp3[['genres','popularity']].values:
    splt = elm1.split('|')
    for elm3 in splt:
        if (elm3 not in category):
            category[elm3] = elm2
        else:
            category[elm3] += elm2
genpop =pd.DataFrame.from_dict(category, orient='index').reset_index()
genpop.columns=['genres', 'sum_popularity']

plt.show()

With the third research question, we want to know which movie genres are most popular throughout the years. To do this we extract the individual genres, $20$ of them, and then we sum the popularity of the movies which fall under the these genres. From the bar plot, we see that $drama$ is the most popular genre, followed by $action$, $comedy$ and $thriller$. This would also mean that most of the popular movies fall under at least one of these individual genres. the genre $foreign$ is the least popular followed closely by $tv movie$.

Research Question 4 (Which genres are most popular from year to year?)¶

In [24]:
temp3 = nmovie_data.groupby(['genres','release_year']).sum().reset_index()

category2 = {}
l = {}
for (elm1,elm2,year) in temp3[['genres','popularity','release_year']].values:
    splt = elm1.split('|')
    if year in category2:
        l = category2[year]
    else:
        l={}
    for elm3 in splt:
        if (elm3 not in l):
            l[elm3] = elm2
        else:
            l[elm3] += elm2
    category2[year] = l
In [25]:
category2 = dict(sorted(category2.items()))
for year in category2:
    dat = category2[year]
    dat =pd.DataFrame.from_dict(dat, orient='index').reset_index()
    dat.columns=['genres', 'sum_popularity']   
    dat.plot.bar(x='genres',y='sum_popularity', color = 'r', ylabel='sum popularity',title=str(year))

Finally we investigate the popularity of genres from year to year. There are a total of $45$ plots one for each year from $1960$ to $2015$. It can be observed that whilethe popularity of a genre varies from year to year, the popular genres have remained fairly stable over the years. The factors that influenced these varitations in the popularity of theses genres maybe external or within the movie industry and are beyond the scope of this study.

Conclusions¶

The investigations carried out on the movie dataset show that there are several factors that could influence the popularity and hence success of a movie, none the less we may not be able to easily generalise these factors to determine the success or popularity of all movies. Additionally, this investigation only scratch the surface of the possible research questions that could be posed on this dataset and is by no means a conclusive study.
